{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Katzav and Vaesen have argued that control by analytic philosophers of key journals, philosophy departments and at least one funding body plays a substantial role in explaining the emergence of analytic philosophy into dominance in the Anglophone world and the corresponding decline of speculative philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "They also argued that this use of control suggests a characterisation of analytic philosophy as, at the institutional level, a sectarian form of critical philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "I argue, further, that Katzav and Vaesen's hypotheses can fully explain the data and are more fully able to do so than some other key accounts of the emergence of analytic philosophy in the USA.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "This involved taking control of key journals, excluding non-analytic philosophy from their pages and founding analytic only journals.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "According to Katzav and Vaesen, the process of marginalisation started in the UK with the takeover of Mind in about 1925 and the founding of the analytic philosophy only journal Analysis in 1933.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "In the USA, the process of marginalisation started with the takeover of The Philosophical Review (PR) in about 1948, involved the takeover of The Journal of Philosophy towards the end of the 1950s and continued at least until the takeover of Philosophy and Phenomenological Research in the late 1970s.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The pressure arising from control of journals appears to have peaked towards the end of the 1950s.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "In addition, the process of marginalisation was facilitated by control by logical empiricists of at least one source of research funding, namely the National Science Foundation's History and Philosophy of Science funding program, and may have been facilitated by control of key philosophy departments, including, from the end of the 1940s, of the Sage School of Philosophy at Cornell and, from the 1950s, of the departments at Harvard and UCLA.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "What was preferred was analytic philosophy, conceived of as a form of critical philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The evidence Katzav and Vaesen collect, however, primarily comprises journals coming under the control of analytic editors and then quickly shifting solely to publishing analytic philosophy.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The data from Strassfeld shows a sharp increase in the ratio of analytic to non-analytic hires at about 1950, one that comes after a period of relative stability of this ratio and reflects a very substantial change in hire trends.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Prior to 1950, hires of analytic philosophers fluctuate between about 30 and 40% of the total number of hires.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Immediately after 1950, analytic hires comprise about 70% of all hires.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The ratio continues to grow in the 1950s and, by the 1960s, analytic hires comprise between about 80 and 90% of all hires.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Contrary to what one might expect, but in accord with Katzav and Vaesen, the RM data on PhD completions does not suggest that these are dominated by analytic topics and supervisors.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "In accordance with (1), the data examined here indicate that there was a sharp increase in the ratio of hires of analytic philosophers to non-analytic philosophers by influential departments from about 1950.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "In accordance with (2), this ratio continued to increase during the 1950s and 1960s.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "In accordance with (3), the data suggest that influential departments start more or less exclusively to hire analytic philosophers in the 1950s and 1960s.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Finally, in accordance with (4), many students completing PhDs in the 1950s were still working outside of what was then analytic philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "In summary, Strassfeld's data and my revision of this data are fully explained by the hypothesis that analytic philosophy gained substantial ground from about 1950 and did so as a result of institutional control.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
